1. Introduction¶

They say you can tell a lot about a man by his dog. But just how much can we infer about a dog's owner by looking at aspects of their pet ownership? In this notebook we'll be exploring the predictive power of various attributes of dog ownership by answering the question: can you predict a dog owner's age given knowledge of their dog's breed, city district, or other fields?

2. Data Collection/Wrangling¶

2A. Zurich Dog Ownership Data¶

The initial dataset I'm using in this project is a record of dogs registered by their owners in Zurich, Switzerland up to 2017.

Downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kmader/dogs-of-zurich?select=20170308hundehalter.csv which was in turn taken from Open Data Zurich.

The immediate issue is that I don't speak German, so we'll first have to do a bit of translation. The column name translation scheme is:

German           English      New Column Name

ALTER  ->          age  ->       human_age_range
GESCHLECHT  ->       gender  ->       human_gender
STADTKREIS  ->       city district  ->    district
RASSE1  ->          primary breed  ->  breed1
RASSE1_MISCHLING  ->   hybrid ->      hybrid 
RASSE2  ->          secondary breed -> breed2
GEBURTSJAHR_HUND  ->   dog birth year  ->  dog_year
GESCHLECHT_HUND  ->   dog gender  ->      dog_gender
HUNDEFARBE  ->        dog color  ->    dog_color

Before we translate the column names, we'll remove the columns we don't care about/can't derive meaning from. (1) HALTER_ID is some kind of person ID used in the Swiss government, but doesn't mean much for our purposes. (2) STADTQUARTIER is a more specific location identifier than district, but district is enough location classification for us. (3) RASSE2_MISCHLING has no values. (4) RASSENTYP is some unclear classification of dog breed, but since we already have detailed breed and hyrid(mix) information, we won't worry about it. We'll drop these four columns:

In [4]:
dogs = dogs.drop(['HALTER_ID', 'STADTQUARTIER', 'RASSE2_MISCHLING', 'RASSENTYP'], axis=1)

Now we translate the column names:

Another translation that needs to be done is within the values for breed1 and breed2. Some values such as 'mop' in breed1 are German versions of breed names. For reasons that will be explained during part 3 (exploratory analysis), we won't worry about translating all of the unique breed values. We'll just translate some of the most popular breed names (we determine popularity later), as these will be the focus of our investigations:

Mischling klein -> small mix
Mischling gross -> large mix
Französische Bulldogge -> French bulldog
Mops -> pug

In [6]:
dogs['breed1'].replace('Mischling klein', 'Small Mix', inplace=True)
dogs['breed1'].replace('Mischling gross', 'Large Mix', inplace=True)
dogs['breed1'].replace('Französische Bulldogge', 'French Bulldog', inplace=True)
dogs['breed1'].replace('Mops', 'Pug', inplace=True)

Translation accuracy wasn't an issue because column names were simple and descriptive in their original German, and also simple German words just tend to translate well using google translate. For extra security, iffy translations were ran by my German-speaking roommate.

As a final note, you might have noticed that our dataset consists of only nominal(categorical) data attributes: discrete age ranges, districts, breed names, and so on. How can we do data science on this set of qualitative attributes? We'll quantify some of these categorical data points into quantitative data. For example, we may want to look into breed popularity trends over time. We can quantify a specific breed's popularity over time by counting the number of births of that breed for each year. In this way, the relative prevalence of qualitative data in our dataset IS quantitative data.

2B. American Kennel Club Breed Information¶

The zurich data gives us the mapping from dog breed to owner age, but lacks quantitative statistics about breeds that we need to hypothesis test. This AKC dataset contains specific attributes like weight, height, and temperament that we could use to make better age predictions down the line. There are 277 breeds.

AKC dog breed attribute data from https://tmfilho.github.io/akcdata/

The task now is to merge this data into our main dataset (dogs) such that entries in dogs have additional columns for height, weight, and energy_level. In order to associate our akc attributes with each entry, we need to match breed names from one to the other. The problem is that some of our breed names in the dogs dataframe are in German whereas akc is in english. My initial plan was to use python's translate package to help with this, but it limits daily translations to some number less than 304 (the number of unique breed names in our main dataset dogs. On top of this, many of the translations would be inexact to the breed names in AKC, so an automated solution is farfetched with my resources. So I made the decision to manually translate the german breed names in dogs to the matching breed names in akc. Translating all 304 breeds by hand would be miserable and for my purposes, I won't need all the data, especially considering that the vast majority of samples fit in a small subset of breed names. So I'll translate the top 40 breeds and use only this subset of the data for the rest of the project.

We'll make a count of each breed, which we'll then use to sort breeds by count, allowing us to see the top 40 breeds.

In [18]:
## make a dict breed1_counts where breed1_counts['<breed>'] is the number of occurances of <breed> in breed1
## initialize each entry (i.e breed) in breed1_counts to 0
breed1_counts = dict((breed,0) for breed in dogs['breed1'].unique())

## count breeds row by row
for index, row in dogs.iterrows():
    breed1_counts[row['breed1']] += 1
    
## check number of dogs counted == number of dogs in original dataset
print(sum(breed1_counts.values()))

## sort our breeds by count:
breed1_counts = dict(sorted(breed1_counts.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))

Note that after cleaning the data of breeds not in the AKC dataset, we have 3897 entries, which is still more than enough.

The AKC dataset had no matching breed for small mix, jack russel terrier, large mix, bolonka, schafer, zwergpinscher, terrier, dackel, podenco, Rauhaar Dackel, spitz, continental bulldog, and husky. That makes 13 breeds we have to throw out, so we need the top 53 to get our desired top 40 breeds. The last step is to merge the height, weight, and energy level from akc to dogs_top40. I set height and weight to be the average of their min and max values.

In [22]:
## merge wegith, height, and energy_level columns into main df
top40 = dogs_top40['breed1'].unique()
dogs_top40['weight'] = 0
dogs_top40['height'] = 0
dogs_top40['energy_level'] = 0
for breed in top40:
    akc_entry = akc[akc['breed'] == breed]
    dogs_top40.loc[dogs_top40['breed1'] == breed, 'weight'] = \
                                            (akc_entry['min_weight'].values[0] + akc_entry['max_weight'].values[0]) / 2
    dogs_top40.loc[dogs_top40['breed1'] == breed, 'height'] = \
                                            (akc_entry['min_height'].values[0] + akc_entry['max_height'].values[0]) / 2
    dogs_top40.loc[dogs_top40['breed1'] == breed, 'energy_level'] = akc_entry['energy_level_value'].values[0]

## Top 10 breed popularity over time

## Build a dataframe: columns are breed count, rows are each year
top10_per_year = pd.DataFrame(index=[i for i in range(1997,2017)])

Some interesting trends can be seen. In the 2000-2015 interval, smaller dog breeds were the dominant type. Small mixes, chihuahuas, and jack russel terriers were having a serious moment of stardom, peaking around 2008, when small mixes and chihuahuas together made up the majority of dogs born that year. Interestingly, chihuahua and small mix births began to decline after 2008, seeming to coincide with an uptick in births for larger dog breeds. After 2008, the golden retriver and large mixes saw significant increases in births per year. Maybe the most pertinent question left unanswered is: why is there a general trend of dropping birth rate from 2011 onward?

3B. Breed Popularity by Age¶

Say your middle-aged parents are moving to Zurich. They are also in the market for a dog, but they want a breed that will be a good fit for their lifestyle. We might want to see what breeds are popular with people their age. Dogs that are owned by mostly younger people may be too rowdy or require too much activity for them. In this section we ask: what is the relationship between age range and breed preference?

To get a general idea of how age affects breed choice, we could start by looking at the average age of the owners of the top 10 breeds. We'll make a violin plot illustrating the distribution of ages for each of the top 10 breeds:

In [27]:
# aggregate age data for each of the top 10 breeds
age_dist_per_breed = []
for breed in top10:
    breed = dogs[dogs['breed1'] == breed]
    age_dist_per_breed.append(breed['human_avg_age'])

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
t = [i for i in range(10)]

# make violinplot with each category corresponding to a breed
ax.violinplot(age_dist_per_breed,t,widths=0.8,showmeans=True)
ax.set_xticks(ticks = t, labels = top10)
ax.set_xlabel("Breed")
ax.set_ylabel("Age")
ax.set_title("Owner Age Distribution for Top 10 Breeds in Zurich")
plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=30, horizontalalignment='right')
fig.savefig("violin_raw_data.png")

Code for slanted xlabels courtesy of 8one6 on stackoverflow.

It turns out that from this relationship we can't pick out a clear pattern of breed preference vs breed size. Small mixes had the oldest mean owner age, but Golden retrievers had the second oldest. Some small dogs are especially popular with a younger population. The french bulldog has by far the lowest average owner age, and further, the breed's violin plot shows that the majority of french bulldog owners are younger than the mean (roughly 38). They must be very trendy in Zurich. By comparison of means, we could say a middle aged or older person would be most satisfied with a small mix, Labrador Retriever, Yorkshire Terrier, or Golder Retriever. If we also consider the distribution about the means (the "swell" of the violins), we'll notice that small mixes and jack russels have distributions that are slightly skewed left, meaning a majority of their owners are older than their mean owner ages (53 and 50 respectively). This points to small mixes and jack russels as especially popular amongst the older generation.

A ridge plot visualizing the same relationship:

4. Hypothesis Testing¶

I believe there is a relationship between dog size and owner age, where as dog size increases, owner age decreases. I decided to use weight as the metric for dog size. We'll fit a linear regression to quantify the strength of this relationship.

null hypothesis: no relationship between dog weight and owner age
alternative hypothesis: as dog weight increases, owner age decreases

In [29]:
from sklearn import linear_model

x = [[x] for x in dogs_top40['weight'].values]
y = [[y] for y in dogs_top40['human_avg_age'].values]
model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model = model.fit(x, y)
model.score(x, y)
print(f" Coefficient of determination: {model.score(x,y)} \n m: {model.coef_[0][0]} \n b: {model.intercept_[0]}")

 Coefficient of determination: 0.0116748661584688 
 m: 0.15219121644706396 
 b: 47.26692813353435
In [30]:
sns.lmplot(x='weight', y='human_avg_age',data=dogs_top40, fit_reg=True, 
           line_kws={'color': 'red'}).fig.suptitle("Owner age by dog Weight")
Out[30]:
Text(0.5, 0.98, 'Owner age by dog Weight')

And it turns out the opposite relationship is true. So we don't adopt the alternative hypothesis, but we can conclude that as dog weight increases, owner age increases. Great! There's definitely a nontrivial relationship.

What about owner age vs the dog's energy level? You'd expect older folks to go for more easygoing dogs, but after the result of the previous test, I reevaluated my logic.

null hypothesis: no relationship between dog energy level and owner age
alternate hypothesis: as energy level increases, age increases

So we accept the alternate hypothesis: as energy level goes up, so does owner age. This could be due to the popularity of easygoing big dogs with the older population, as was seen earlier in particular with golden and labrador retrievers.

Predicting Age: classify an owner's age using breed, district, year, etc¶

We'll attempt to classify an owner's age based on the quantifiable attributes of their dog ownership.

human_gender, breed1, dog_gender, and dog_color are all not numerical data, so we'll have to encode them for our model to make sense of. Human_gender and dog_gender resolve to either m or w (discussion of the gender binary is outside the scope of this class) so we can encode them as 0 and 1 respectively. breed1 and dog_color are more complex strings which I'll do a custom encoding of each.

Encoding dog_gender and human_gender:

In [33]:
dogs = dogs_top40
for index, row in dogs.iterrows():
    if row['dog_gender'] == 'm':
        dogs.at[index, 'dog_gender'] = 0
    elif row['dog_gender'] == 'w':
        dogs.at[index, 'dog_gender'] = 1
for index, row in dogs.iterrows():
    if row['human_gender'] == 'm':
        dogs.at[index, 'human_gender'] = 0
    elif row['human_gender'] == 'w':
        dogs.at[index, 'human_gender'] = 1

Encoding breed1:

In [34]:
dogs["breed1_enc"] = 0
encodings = {}
i = 0 # current encoding

# encode each breed in breed1 to integer in a new column in dogs
for index, row in dogs.iterrows():
    breed = row['breed1']
    if breed not in encodings.keys(): # if breed is not in encodings
        encodings[breed] = i # store encoding
        i += 1 
    dogs.at[index, 'breed1_enc'] = encodings[breed]

Encoding dog_color:

5. Conclusions¶

This project set out with the goal of identifying trends in dog ownership in Zurich, Switzerland. Through amalgamation of two datasets I was able to identify breed popularity trends over time and by owner age. Posh small breeds like pugs and french bulldogs have been the clear favorite of younger dog owners in the 2000-2015 time interval. In that same interval, easygoing larger breeds like golden and labrador retrievers were the most popular breeds for older people. Through hypothesis testing, it was discovered that as breed weight increases, owner age increases. A linear regression fitted to a plot of owner age vs dog weight had a slope of 0.15, meaning that roughly for every 6 pound increase in dog weight, owner age could be expected to grow by 1 year. Through building and analyzing the predictive capabilities of three different supervised ML models, I found that the Zurich dataset was actually too stochastic to build a powerful owner age classifier. This is a disappointing result, but it answers our initial research question and suggests that in order to build a better classifier, we'd need access to some combination of more entries (rows in the Zurich dataset) and predictors (columns in the Zurich dataset). Perhaps additional attributes, whether the dog is mixed with other breeds for example, would give us enough for more accurate classification.
